column1: The data are expressed in microdata format, that is, one row per character and one column per variable. All major and minor characters from the selected books are included, except for the murder victims.

column3: The book in which the character features, for example, Murder in Mesopotamia
The character’s name, for example, Elspeth McGillicudy
“1” if the character is a murderer; “0” otherwise
A series of indicator variables denoting occupation. These are:
Medical, for example, doctors, nurses and dentists
Servant, for example, cooks and maids.
Military, for example, majors and colonels
AristocratWealthy, for example, aristocrats and “rich” characters
Skilled; a “skilled occupation”, for example, chemists and architects
Business; those who have their own business
Arts; for example, painters and writers
Housewife/Spinster/Widow; a common Agatha Christie character, for example, Miss Marple herself
A count for the number of times each murder weapon was used in the book. This variable is at the “book” level, not the “character” level.
The number of murders in the book.
“1" if the book is set in England; “0” otherwise
